##The outbreak of coronavirus is not accidental? Study shows: Virus"overflow"phenomenon or already happened stealthily for many years

From DeepTech

There are still many questions about how the new coronavirus got from animals to humans, and whether it will return in the future? Although the answer is largely speculative, some bat scientists say the coronavirus outbreak was no accident.

When Shi Zhengli's team at the Wuhan Virus Research Institute compared the virus with Chinese rufous Horseshoe Bat from southern China at the beginning of the new crown outbreak in China, they found more than 96.2 percent genetic homology, and the new coronavirus is a distant relative of SARS 17 years ago, with 79.5 percent of their genetic sequences identical, locking in the natural host, or bat, of COVID-19.

In nature, there are many types of viruses that occasionally cross populations and spread to humans and other animals. This is what virologists fear as a "spill-over" of viruses, eating game such as bats may even come from Chinese medicine.

Fig. | discussion on the relationship between coronaviruses and bat traditional Chinese Medicine Derivatives (Source: SFAM)

Chinese Medicine "night-bright Sand" is made of bat faeces, used to treat eye diseases or detoxification. Now, a German expert in molecular microbiology and genomics, Trudy M. In his study, Wassenaar speculates that the whole chain of capturing, processing, selling and Ingesting Wild Bat derivatives of traditional Chinese medicine, a natural reservoir of coronavirus in the bat species, may pose a significant potential risk to the spread of zoonosis.

But researchers at the non-profit Research Group ECOHEALTH Alliance have found that the coronavirus "overflow" from bats may have been happening quietly in China for years, sars-associated coronavirus in some bat populations can infect human hosts without even an additional step of mutation.

For the past 10 years, the alliance has worked with Chinese scientists, said Professor Peter Daszak, an American infectious disease scientist who chairs the Alliance, writing in Biosafety and Health, samples from more than 10,000 bats and about 2,000 other mammals were collected in southern China, and 52 new SARS associated coronavirus and a large number of other coronavirus were found.

These studies suggest that wild-origin coronavirus is a "clear and present danger, " and that many coronaviruses have pandemic potential when we do not hesitate to come into direct or indirect contact, could be the trigger for the next outbreak.

The researchers captured a bat and sampled it (Source: Ecological Health Alliance) 

01
Coronaviruses may be triggered more directly

In a study published in 2013 in Nature in collaboration with the Alliance for Ecological Health and Shi's team, researchers isolated an active SL-CoV from bat feces samples. The SARS-associated coronavirus (SARSr-CoVs) has a typical coronavirus shape, 99.9% of its sequence homology is RS3367, and it can invade human body through ACE2 receptor cells, which indicates that SARSr-CoVs may have high potential to infect human cells, without an intermediate host.

In 2018, the two sides published a new study in the Chinese Journal of Virology, again investigating serological evidence of SARS associated coronavirus infection in Chinese bats. For the study, the team monitored the serology of people living near the cave. The sample included 218 residents living within 1.1-6.0 km of the Cave's perimeter. 81.2% of the sample had livestock or pets and 97.2% had a history of contact with livestock or wild animals. What's more, 9.1 percent saw bats flying near their homes.
For those at high risk of living near a bat colony, the detection rate was 2.7 percent, suggesting that Seroprevalence is a relatively rare event, and also depends on how long the antibody lasts in the body, six seropositive subjects did not recall any clinical symptoms over the past 12 months.

Li Hongying, an expert in epidemiology and social sciences at the eco-health Alliance, told Deeptech that the spill occurred in nature, but that several factors were needed to co-ordinate the spread of the virus, these include the ecological, epidemiological and behavioral determinants of pathogen exposure, as well as human internal factors that influence susceptibility to infection... we can prevent this if we know some of the risks.

Over the past decade, Li's team has conducted biological and behavioral surveillance of people in close contact with bat habitats, where coronavirus infections and viral overflows have also been detected, although this is quite different from the current new coronavirus, and the positive rate is low, but these lab results have shown potential red flags.

The risk may be higher if it is direct contact with bats or their droppings. German expert Trudy M. In the study, Wassenaar speculates that bats may have been or have been sold on the food market in Wuhan, a city with an epidemic of NCP, and that bats and their droppings are often used in traditional Chinese medicine, live or recently dead infected bat species are handled by traders because of their medicinal value.

In the trade chain, host jumps occur between infected bats and other mammals, which in turn can become a source of infection. Even if the sale of live wild animals on the food market is completely banned in China, the trade and handling of bats using traditional medical practices will remain a serious risk of a future zoonotic coronavirus epidemic.

Overall, the route of coronavirus outbreaks may be more direct, with all kinds of active or passive "overflow" events causing bat viruses to enter the human body, resulting in regional or medicinal infections, and cause a worldwide pandemic.

The researchers took viral samples of captured bats and explored caves where the bats were hiding (Source: Alliance for Ecological Health) 

02
High risk and low consciousness

Most of the Emerging Infectious Diseases that afflict humans are zoonotic -- HIV, Zaire Ebolavirus, SARS, Mers, and so on -- can be traced to specific wild animals, but for a long time, few Analytical tools are available to determine which host species might carry the next virus that sweeps through humans, or which might cross the species boundary directly.

In 2017, ecologists at the evolutionary biology and a team of Kevin Olival at the University of California, Berkeley, conducted a comprehensive analysis of the relationship between Mammalian hosts and viruses, the study, published in the June 2017 issue of the authoritative journal Nature, shows that the total number of viruses infecting a species and the proportion that could cause zoonosis are actually predictable.

The team created and analyzed a database of 2,805 mammalian virus associations, including 754 mammalian species from 15 destinations (representing 14 percent of Global Mammalian diversity) and 586 unique viral species from 28 viral families. The results showed that bats, primates and rodents had higher rates of zoonosis than other mammal groups.

Figure | heat map of total virus abundance observed in the order mammalidae and virology, including 754 mammal species and 586 unique virus species recognized by ICTV (Source: Nature) 

Bunia, flaviviruses and sand viruses are most abundant in rodents; flaviviruses, Bunia and rhabdoviruses are most abundant in bats; and non-human primates, the herpesvirus is the most abundant. The study also showed that wild bats (PTEROPODS) carried significantly higher rates of zoonosis than all other mammals in the study sample.

The observed abundance of Mammalian viruses: A, the proportion of zoonosis; b, the total virus abundance of each species, Gray Wild, red domesticated (Source: Nature) 

It is possible to predict the global distribution of hot spots for emerging infectious disease based on the distribution of wild animals with high rates of zoonosis.

In recent years, Emerging Infectious Diseases have become increasingly prominent and serious threats to global health, the economy and security, and their frequency of outbreaks and economic impact have increased, but our understanding of the causes of disease is incomplete, scientists have only observed that almost all recent viral pandemics have their origin in animals, primarily in the dynamic interactions between wild and domestic animal populations, and in less sensitive people in such rapidly changing environments.

Over the past decade, the ECO Health Alliance, in collaboration with Chinese scientists, has collected samples from more than 10,000 bats and about 2,000 other mammal species in southern China, 52 New SARS-associated coronaviruses, 122 other coronaviruses, more than 350 new coronaviruses and a new "lineage e"-coronaviruses were found, marks the wildlife-derived coronavirus as a "clear and present danger" , and many coronaviruses have pandemic potential.

Another study, in which Olival was involved, established an analytical model to attempt to assess the Eid and showed that the areas suitable for Eid were relatively evenly distributed over the entire continent. In theory, the Eid risk index would increase in areas with high tropical forest environments and High Mammalian Biodiversity. However, on the basis of natural environmental conditions, Eid risk indices are stacked in many countries and cities in densely populated areas such as Europe, the United States, Asia and Latin America.

Fig. | thermodynamic diagram of the relative risk distribution of the Eid event for zoonotic disease predicted by the model after population reweighting (Source: Nature) 

On a predictive thermodynamic chart, China's Eid risk value is very prominent, and high-risk areas without prevention and control and prevention awareness is dangerous.

Together with Olival, Li took part in research on bats and went to China to collect samples. She has found that some villagers in southern China may have inadvertently come into contact with the bats'saliva or excrement in a variety of ways, even living near their nests.

Many people in the study reported finding bats in their homes, flying into my house, killing it or finding bats eating fruit from the yard. In the summer, some of the caves where the bats are hiding may be used as a place for people to meet to relieve the heat, and when the team searches the caves for bat samples, it is common to see people leaving behind beer and water bottles.

When asked, do locals catch bats and sell them to restaurants? Yes, "bats are said to prevent cancer" and "nourish life" . Overall, many of the researchers said that hunting, trade or consumption of wildlife has declined in recent years; however, there are still wild animals (rodents, bats, feral cats, frogs, snakes and birds) that are hunted or eaten locally for entertainment or income, and many people believe that wildlife or its by-products have health benefits.

From October 2015 to July 2017, Li Hongying's team surveyed a total of 1,596 residents from eight sites in Yunnan (761) , Guangxi (412) and Guangdong (423) provinces, testing serum samples for bat-transmitted coronavirus, nine participants (0.6%) tested positive for bat coronavirus and 265(17%) reported severe symptoms of acute respiratory tract infection or influenza-like illness (Ili) , these symptoms are associated with exposure to poultry, predators, rodents, or bats.

Figure | classification and activity of animal exposure, with the red number in the upper right corner representing the number of seropositive people in the group Source: ScienceDirect

Research has observed that coronaviruses may have spread to humans, but these are small outbreaks that are not taken seriously, even in individuals with symptoms of the disease, however, it is not sufficient to identify the risk of transmission of the epidemic and to trigger strong action by local health authorities.

03
Will coronaviruses make a comeback?

The new coronavirus outbreak follows two previous outbreaks of coronavirus in China, both of which have caused significant public health incidents and varying degrees of economic damage. Fortunately, not all of the viruses have infected people.

Sars-cov originated in Guangdong, China, and then spread around the world, infecting more than 8,000 people with a total mortality rate of 10 per cent during the 2002-2003 pandemic, while the other, SADS-CoV, attacked the pig industry in 2016-2017, killing more than 20,000 piglets.

Bats are considered as important natural hosts of coronaviruses, and the Association of Coronaviruses With Bat Studies is of certain reference significance for the prevention and control of Chinese epidemic situation. Researchers generally believe that bat coronavirus will re-emerge to trigger the next outbreak, and in this regard, China may be a high-risk area. And the big challenge is to warn when and where it might happen, so that we do our best to prevent it from happening again and again.

In March 2019, Shi Zhengli's team at the Chinese Academy of Sciences published a paper investigating the distribution of bat coronavirus in China, the geographic distribution of bat coronaviruses and their corresponding bat hosts in China were revealed.

As shown in the figure below, each red box represents a CoV positive sample found in that particular bat species, and a dot matrix is drawn for each province reporting a Cov positive sample, indicating abbreviations for bat species and virus species. Guangdong Province, where SARS and SADS broke out, is circled with red circles. In addition, we can see that Yunnan, Guizhou and Hubei have high diversity and clustering, and may also be the hot spots where viruses spill over. This Hubei becomes the new crown epidemic situation heavy disaster area, it seems that the side confirms this point.

The distribution of bat coronavirus in China (Source: VIRUSES)

In order to predict the next outbreak caused by coronavirus, Shi Zhengli's team had listed in the paper the general factors that might lead to an outbreak of coronavirus.

First, bats have a large population of highly diverse coronaviruses, whose genomes are known to recombine regularly during infection, a process facilitated by a rich gene pool, bats are widely distributed and live near humans; third, viruses are pathogenic and transmissible.

In this context, the outbreak of SARS-CoV, SADS-CoV and now the new coronavirus in China does not seem to be a coincidence, and it is worth noting that there are other hot-spot coronaviruses that have not yet become endemic and should be closely monitored.

Although the exact manner in which the deadly new coronavirus spread in China and how it got there from animals to humans remains a mystery, scientists generally agree that, this is closely related to the dense mobility of the urban population and the chaotic and loosely regulated free and open market.

There are so called wet markets in parts of southern China, as well as in Vietnam, Indonesia and other parts of Southeast Asia, where wild and domesticated animals are cross farmed and almost always slaughtered in unhygienic ways, all of these factors provide the perfect mix for viral spills, which, if unchecked, can lead to deadly new viruses every few years or inevitably.

In many wet markets, snakes, bats and other wild animals are piled in wire mesh cages, and traditional Chinese food culture generally considers freshly slaughtered animals to be more nutritious. A mixture of fluids and secretions that carry the virus can help produce new viruses, especially when the animals are slaughtered in front of customers, which can increase the chances of the virus infecting more people.

In addition, outbreaks in the past may have had an impact only in local areas. Now, with a surging migrant population and accelerating infrastructure such as aviation, high speed rail and high speed rail, the bat virus can be brought to market from the depths of the jungle and spread to every corner of the globe within days.

04
Strategies to prevent the next viral pandemic

Reality is always harsher than ideal. Although research on Bat viruses and related viruses has invested a great deal of effort on the part of researchers, the COVID-19 has spread infection both within China and internationally, although modern medical techniques can analyze all the characteristics of coronavirus associated with bat origin, the mechanism of viral spillover that causes human infections remains uncertain.

There is no doubt, however, that trade in wildlife carries an inherent risk of exposing people to pathogens carried by wildlife, and we need to think now to prepare for the next new coronavirus pandemic.

In response, a report by Peter Daszak, Kevin Olival and Li Hongying suggests several targeted prevention strategies:

1. Monitor wildlife for high risk pathogens.

This is also the most critical issue in the early warning of the epidemic. The wide variety of strains of the virus in the wild in China and their high probability of appearing in humans urge scientists in the relevant fields to work hard to find all of these viruses, to classify them, develop a reference library for rapid pathogen identification and risk assessment, and test vaccines and therapies for hotspot viruses.

2. Monitor and reduce the risk to high-risk populations exposed to wildlife.

Individual cases or a small group of infections may escape surveillance, especially in areas of poor health care in China or in rural areas where people do not seek prompt diagnosis or treatment. Local public health authorities can design monitoring programmes to identify areas with high wildlife diversity and high risk of novel viruses; People who make a living from frequent contact with wild or domestic animals, as well as patients with unexplained symptoms of acute respiratory tract infection or influenza-like illness, could be included as a cost-effective approach, identifying novel virus overflows.

This "pre-outbreak monitoring" strategy could coordinate with different sectors such as public health, Health Care, agriculture and forestry, and work with research institutions to collect and test samples from wildlife, livestock and humans, then identify high-risk groups and potential risk factors.

3. Improve wildlife trade and biosecurity in animal markets.

Low levels of environmental biosafety and high levels of human-animal exposure have been identified as key risk factors for the emergence of zoonosis in China, particularly in local wet markets and animal markets, while the current mandatory wildlife trade ban may help in disease control at this time, it is important to prevent future disease, market Biosafety still requires strong monitoring of health regulations, sanitation facilities and sources of traded animals on the market.

In general, there are still limitations in previous studies that can not accurately assess the risk of bat coronavirus overflow due to low Seroprevalence, she said in an e mail response to DeepTech, the small number of seropositive cases detected were also unrelated to direct contact with bats, so prevention strategies can only be described in general terms as reducing human contact with wild animals and increasing environmental biosecurity.

And one of the big drivers of disease is also closely linked to human activity, which is expanding globally, including deforestation, agricultural intensification and Wildlife Trade, this has led to a dramatic increase in the frequency of animal-to-human contact, an exponential increase in the likelihood of the emergence and spread of new diseases, and the likelihood that pandemics will become more frequent and destructive in the future.

We are facing the unknown, global environmental changes are driving the emergence of new diseases.

Even if the sale of live wild animals on the food market is completely banned in China, the trade and handling of bats using traditional medical practices will remain a serious risk of a future zoonotic coronavirus epidemic.

Overall, the route of coronavirus outbreaks may be more direct, with all kinds of active or passive "overflow" events causing bat viruses to enter the human body, resulting in regional or medicinal infections, and cause a worldwide pandemic.

02
High risk and low consciousness

02

High risk and low consciousness

Most of the Emerging Infectious Diseases that afflict humans are zoonotic -- HIV, Zaire Ebolavirus, SARS, Mers, and so on -- can be traced to specific wild animals, but for a long time, few Analytical tools are available to determine which host species might carry the next virus that sweeps through humans, or which might cross the species boundary directly.

In 2017, ecologists at the evolutionary biology and a team of Kevin Olival at the University of California, Berkeley, conducted a comprehensive analysis of the relationship between Mammalian hosts and viruses, the study, published in the June 2017 issue of the authoritative journal Nature, shows that the total number of viruses infecting a species and the proportion that could cause zoonosis are actually predictable.

The team created and analyzed a database of 2,805 mammalian virus associations, including 754 mammalian species from 15 destinations (representing 14 percent of Global Mammalian diversity) and 586 unique viral species from 28 viral families. The results showed that bats, primates and rodents had higher rates of zoonosis than other mammal groups.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | heat map of total virus abundance observed in the order mammalidae and virology, including 754 mammal species and 586 unique virus species recognized by ICTV (Source: Nature) 

Bunia, flaviviruses and sand viruses are most abundant in rodents; flaviviruses, Bunia and rhabdoviruses are most abundant in bats; and non-human primates, the herpesvirus is the most abundant. The study also showed that wild bats (PTEROPODS) carried significantly higher rates of zoonosis than all other mammals in the study sample.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The observed abundance of Mammalian viruses: A, the proportion of zoonosis; b, the total virus abundance of each species, Gray Wild, red domesticated (Source: Nature) 

It is possible to predict the global distribution of hot spots for emerging infectious disease based on the distribution of wild animals with high rates of zoonosis.

In recent years, Emerging Infectious Diseases have become increasingly prominent and serious threats to global health, the economy and security, and their frequency of outbreaks and economic impact have increased, but our understanding of the causes of disease is incomplete, scientists have only observed that almost all recent viral pandemics have their origin in animals, primarily in the dynamic interactions between wild and domestic animal populations, and in less sensitive people in such rapidly changing environments.

Over the past decade, the ECO Health Alliance, in collaboration with Chinese scientists, has collected samples from more than 10,000 bats and about 2,000 other mammal species in southern China, 52 New SARS-associated coronaviruses, 122 other coronaviruses, more than 350 new coronaviruses and a new "lineage e"-coronaviruses were found, marks the wildlife-derived coronavirus as a "clear and present danger" , and many coronaviruses have pandemic potential.

Another study, in which Olival was involved, established an analytical model to attempt to assess the Eid and showed that the areas suitable for Eid were relatively evenly distributed over the entire continent. In theory, the Eid risk index would increase in areas with high tropical forest environments and High Mammalian Biodiversity. However, on the basis of natural environmental conditions, Eid risk indices are stacked in many countries and cities in densely populated areas such as Europe, the United States, Asia and Latin America.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. | thermodynamic diagram of the relative risk distribution of the Eid event for zoonotic disease predicted by the model after population reweighting (Source: Nature) 

On a predictive thermodynamic chart, China's Eid risk value is very prominent, and high-risk areas without prevention and control and prevention awareness is dangerous.

Together with Olival, Li took part in research on bats and went to China to collect samples. She has found that some villagers in southern China may have inadvertently come into contact with the bats'saliva or excrement in a variety of ways, even living near their nests.

Many people in the study reported finding bats in their homes, flying into my house, killing it or finding bats eating fruit from the yard. In the summer, some of the caves where the bats are hiding may be used as a place for people to meet to relieve the heat, and when the team searches the caves for bat samples, it is common to see people leaving behind beer and water bottles.

When asked, do locals catch bats and sell them to restaurants? Yes, "bats are said to prevent cancer" and "nourish life" . Overall, many of the researchers said that hunting, trade or consumption of wildlife has declined in recent years; however, there are still wild animals (rodents, bats, feral cats, frogs, snakes and birds) that are hunted or eaten locally for entertainment or income, and many people believe that wildlife or its by-products have health benefits.

From October 2015 to July 2017, Li Hongying's team surveyed a total of 1,596 residents from eight sites in Yunnan (761) , Guangxi (412) and Guangdong (423) provinces, testing serum samples for bat-transmitted coronavirus, nine participants (0.6%) tested positive for bat coronavirus and 265(17%) reported severe symptoms of acute respiratory tract infection or influenza-like illness (Ili) , these symptoms are associated with exposure to poultry, predators, rodents, or bats.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | classification and activity of animal exposure, with the red number in the upper right corner representing the number of seropositive people in the group Source: ScienceDirect

Research has observed that coronaviruses may have spread to humans, but these are small outbreaks that are not taken seriously, even in individuals with symptoms of the disease, however, it is not sufficient to identify the risk of transmission of the epidemic and to trigger strong action by local health authorities.

03
Will coronaviruses make a comeback?

03

Will coronaviruses make a comeback?

The new coronavirus outbreak follows two previous outbreaks of coronavirus in China, both of which have caused significant public health incidents and varying degrees of economic damage. Fortunately, not all of the viruses have infected people.

Sars-cov originated in Guangdong, China, and then spread around the world, infecting more than 8,000 people with a total mortality rate of 10 per cent during the 2002-2003 pandemic, while the other, SADS-CoV, attacked the pig industry in 2016-2017, killing more than 20,000 piglets.

Bats are considered as important natural hosts of coronaviruses, and the Association of Coronaviruses With Bat Studies is of certain reference significance for the prevention and control of Chinese epidemic situation. Researchers generally believe that bat coronavirus will re-emerge to trigger the next outbreak, and in this regard, China may be a high-risk area. And the big challenge is to warn when and where it might happen, so that we do our best to prevent it from happening again and again.

In March 2019, Shi Zhengli's team at the Chinese Academy of Sciences published a paper investigating the distribution of bat coronavirus in China, the geographic distribution of bat coronaviruses and their corresponding bat hosts in China were revealed.

As shown in the figure below, each red box represents a CoV positive sample found in that particular bat species, and a dot matrix is drawn for each province reporting a Cov positive sample, indicating abbreviations for bat species and virus species. Guangdong Province, where SARS and SADS broke out, is circled with red circles. In addition, we can see that Yunnan, Guizhou and Hubei have high diversity and clustering, and may also be the hot spots where viruses spill over. This Hubei becomes the new crown epidemic situation heavy disaster area, it seems that the side confirms this point.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The distribution of bat coronavirus in China (Source: VIRUSES)

In order to predict the next outbreak caused by coronavirus, Shi Zhengli's team had listed in the paper the general factors that might lead to an outbreak of coronavirus.

First, bats have a large population of highly diverse coronaviruses, whose genomes are known to recombine regularly during infection, a process facilitated by a rich gene pool, bats are widely distributed and live near humans; third, viruses are pathogenic and transmissible.

In this context, the outbreak of SARS-CoV, SADS-CoV and now the new coronavirus in China does not seem to be a coincidence, and it is worth noting that there are other hot-spot coronaviruses that have not yet become endemic and should be closely monitored.

Although the exact manner in which the deadly new coronavirus spread in China and how it got there from animals to humans remains a mystery, scientists generally agree that, this is closely related to the dense mobility of the urban population and the chaotic and loosely regulated free and open market.

There are so called wet markets in parts of southern China, as well as in Vietnam, Indonesia and other parts of Southeast Asia, where wild and domesticated animals are cross farmed and almost always slaughtered in unhygienic ways, all of these factors provide the perfect mix for viral spills, which, if unchecked, can lead to deadly new viruses every few years or inevitably.

In many wet markets, snakes, bats and other wild animals are piled in wire mesh cages, and traditional Chinese food culture generally considers freshly slaughtered animals to be more nutritious. A mixture of fluids and secretions that carry the virus can help produce new viruses, especially when the animals are slaughtered in front of customers, which can increase the chances of the virus infecting more people.

In addition, outbreaks in the past may have had an impact only in local areas. Now, with a surging migrant population and accelerating infrastructure such as aviation, high speed rail and high speed rail, the bat virus can be brought to market from the depths of the jungle and spread to every corner of the globe within days.

04
Strategies to prevent the next viral pandemic

04

Strategies to prevent the next viral pandemic

Reality is always harsher than ideal. Although research on Bat viruses and related viruses has invested a great deal of effort on the part of researchers, the COVID-19 has spread infection both within China and internationally, although modern medical techniques can analyze all the characteristics of coronavirus associated with bat origin, the mechanism of viral spillover that causes human infections remains uncertain.

There is no doubt, however, that trade in wildlife carries an inherent risk of exposing people to pathogens carried by wildlife, and we need to think now to prepare for the next new coronavirus pandemic.

In response, a report by Peter Daszak, Kevin Olival and Li Hongying suggests several targeted prevention strategies:

1. Monitor wildlife for high risk pathogens.

This is also the most critical issue in the early warning of the epidemic. The wide variety of strains of the virus in the wild in China and their high probability of appearing in humans urge scientists in the relevant fields to work hard to find all of these viruses, to classify them, develop a reference library for rapid pathogen identification and risk assessment, and test vaccines and therapies for hotspot viruses.

2. Monitor and reduce the risk to high-risk populations exposed to wildlife.

Individual cases or a small group of infections may escape surveillance, especially in areas of poor health care in China or in rural areas where people do not seek prompt diagnosis or treatment. Local public health authorities can design monitoring programmes to identify areas with high wildlife diversity and high risk of novel viruses; People who make a living from frequent contact with wild or domestic animals, as well as patients with unexplained symptoms of acute respiratory tract infection or influenza-like illness, could be included as a cost-effective approach, identifying novel virus overflows.

This "pre-outbreak monitoring" strategy could coordinate with different sectors such as public health, Health Care, agriculture and forestry, and work with research institutions to collect and test samples from wildlife, livestock and humans, then identify high-risk groups and potential risk factors.

3. Improve wildlife trade and biosecurity in animal markets.

Low levels of environmental biosafety and high levels of human-animal exposure have been identified as key risk factors for the emergence of zoonosis in China, particularly in local wet markets and animal markets, while the current mandatory wildlife trade ban may help in disease control at this time, it is important to prevent future disease, market Biosafety still requires strong monitoring of health regulations, sanitation facilities and sources of traded animals on the market.

In general, there are still limitations in previous studies that can not accurately assess the risk of bat coronavirus overflow due to low Seroprevalence, she said in an e mail response to DeepTech, the small number of seropositive cases detected were also unrelated to direct contact with bats, so prevention strategies can only be described in general terms as reducing human contact with wild animals and increasing environmental biosecurity.

And one of the big drivers of disease is also closely linked to human activity, which is expanding globally, including deforestation, agricultural intensification and Wildlife Trade, this has led to a dramatic increase in the frequency of animal-to-human contact, an exponential increase in the likelihood of the emergence and spread of new diseases, and the likelihood that pandemics will become more frequent and destructive in the future.

We are facing the unknown, global environmental changes are driving the emergence of new diseases.
